	abstract = {{\textbackslash}textlessi{\textbackslash}{textgreaterContext}.{\textbackslash}textlessi/{\textbackslash}textgreater The availability of asteroseismic constraints for a large sample of stars from the missions {CoRoT} and {\textbackslash}textlessi{\textbackslash}{textgreaterKepler} {\textbackslash}textlessi/{\textbackslash}textgreaterpaves the way for various statistical studies of the seismic properties of stellar populations.{\textbackslash}textlessi{\textbackslash}{textgreaterAims}.{\textbackslash}textlessi/{\textbackslash}textgreater We evaluate the impact of rotation-induced mixing and thermohaline instability on the global asteroseismic parameters at different stages of the stellar evolution from the zero age main sequence to the thermally pulsating asymptotic giant branch to distinguish stellar populations.{\textbackslash}textlessi{\textbackslash}{textgreaterMethods}.{\textbackslash}textlessi/{\textbackslash}textgreater We present a grid of stellar evolutionary models for four metallicities ({\textbackslash}textlessi{\textbackslash}{textgreaterZ}{\textbackslash}textlessi/{\textbackslash}textgreater = 0.0001, 0.002, 0.004, and 0.014) in the mass range from 0.85 to 6.0 {\textbackslash}textlessi{\textbackslash}{textgreaterM}{\textbackslash}textlessi/{\textbackslash}textgreater{\textbackslash}textlesssub{\textbackslash}textgreater⊙{\textbackslash}textlesssub/{\textbackslash}textgreater. The models are computed either with standard prescriptions or including both thermohaline convection and rotation-induced mixing. For the whole grid, we provide the usual stellar parameters (luminosity, effective temperature, lifetimes, ... ), together with the global seismic parameters, i.e. the large frequency separation and asymptotic relations, the frequency corresponding to the maximum oscillation power {\textbackslash}textlessi{\textbackslash}textgreaterν{\textbackslash}textlessi/{\textbackslash}textgreater{\textbackslash}textlesssub{\textbackslash}textgreatermax{