	abstract = {We analyze K2 light curves for 132 low-mass ({\textbackslash}1{\textbackslash}textbackslash {\textbackslash}textbackslashgtrsim{\textbackslash}textbackslash M\_*{\textbackslash}textbackslash {\textbackslash}textbackslashgtrsim{\textbackslash}textbackslash 0.1\{{\textbackslash}textasciitilde\{M\_\{{\textbackslash}textbackslashodot\}\}{\textbackslash}) members of the 600–800{\textbackslash}{textasciitildeMyr}-old Hyades cluster and measure rotation periods ({\textbackslash}P\_\{rot\}{\textbackslash}) for 116 of these stars. These include 93 stars with no prior {\textbackslash}P\_\{rot\}{\textbackslash} measurement; the total number of Hyads with known {\textbackslash}P\_\{rot\}{\textbackslash} is now 232. We then combine literature binary data with Gaia {DR}2 photometry and astrometry to select single star sequences in the Hyades and its roughly coeval Praesepe open cluster, and derive a new reddening value of {\textbackslash}A\_V = 0.035\{{\textbackslash}textbackslashpm{\textbackslash}0.011{\textbackslash} for Praesepe. Comparing the effective temperature–{\textbackslash}P\_\{rot\}{\textbackslash} distributions for the Hyades and Praesepe, we find that solar-type Hyads rotate, on average, 0.4{\textbackslash}textasciitilded slower than their Praesepe counterparts. This {\textbackslash}P\_\{rot\}{\textbackslash} difference indicates that the Hyades is slightly older than Praesepe: we apply a new gyrochronology model tuned with Praesepe and the Sun, and find an age difference between the two clusters of 57{\textbackslash}{textasciitildeMyr}. However, this {\textbackslash}P\_\{rot\}{\textbackslash} difference decreases and eventually disappears for lower-mass stars. This provides further evidence for stalling in the rotational evolution of these stars, and highlights the need for more detailed analysis of angular-momentum evolution for stars of different masses and ages.},
